<article>
    <h1>Coun&#xAD;try&#x2019;s pot of gold</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200811/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-11"><time>2020-08-11</time></a>
        - <span>BUSINESS</span>
        - <span role="byline">Ar&#xAD;lina Ar&#xAD;shad</span>
    </section>

    <p>From space, the gap­ing hole of the Gras­berg open-pit mine sit­ting in the high­lands of In­done­sia’s Pa­pua prov­ince is un­mis­tak­able.</p>
    <p>Here, in the world’s largest gold mine and sec­ond-largest cop­per mine, 15 bil­lion kg of cop­per and 1.5 mil­lion kg of gold have been un­earthed from 1990 to last year, ac­cord­ing to the web­site of United States min­ing gi­ant Freeport-McMoRan, which op­er­ates the fa­cil­ity through its sub­sidiary, Freeport In­done­sia.</p>
    <p>Some 12.5 bil­lion kg of cop­per and 1.3 mil­lion kg of gold had come from the open pit, it added.</p>
    <p>In­done­sia is among the world’s top 10 gold pro­duc­ers, with out­put reach­ing 109.2 tonnes last year, ac­cord­ing to the Min­istry of En­ergy and Min­eral Re­sources. That ac­counts for around 4 per cent of global gold pro­duc­tion.</p>
    <p>Be­sides Pa­pua, In­done­sia’s largest gold mines can be found on Sum­bawa is­land in West Nusa Teng­gara, and in East Kal­i­man­tan and Cen­tral Kal­i­man­tan prov­inces. But more than half of the coun­try’s gold orig­i­nates from Gras­berg, where work is on­go­ing to con­vert the open pit into an un­der­ground mine.</p>
    <p>A drawn-out dis­pute over Gras­berg’s own­er­ship ended in 2018 af­ter the In­done­sian gov­ern­ment took 51 per cent con­trol of Freeport In­done­sia’s shares, up from 9.36 per cent, in a US$3.5 bil­lion (S$4.8 bil­lion) deal.</p>

